docs.abstract: The deal comes amid a flurry of exemptions and revisions to the steel and aluminum protections announced this month by the White House.
docs.snippet: The deal comes amid a flurry of exemptions and revisions to the steel and aluminum protections announced this month by the White House.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump is on the verge of securing his first major trade deal, leveraging the threat of tariffs to gain concessions from South Korea on exports of steel and imports of American cars.

headline.main: Trump Gets First Major Trade Deal as South Korea Looks to Avoid Tariffs
headline.print_headline: South Korea, Looking to Avoid Tariffs, Agrees to U.S. Trade Deal

byline.original: By Alan Rappeport and Jim Tankersley

docs.abstract: In a shift in strategy, the White House may impose import quotas to prevent too much foreign metal from flooding into the United States.
docs.snippet: In a shift in strategy, the White House may impose import quotas to prevent too much foreign metal from flooding into the United States.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration began imposing stiff tariffs on imported steel and aluminum early on Friday morning. But it granted a brief exemption to some allies, and in a twist, said it might impose import quotas to prevent too much foreign metal from flooding into the United States.

headline.main: U.S. Exempts Some Allies From Tariffs, but May Opt for Quotas

byline.original: By Jim Tankersley and Natalie Kitroeff

docs.abstract: The Federal Reserve, buoyed by a strengthening economy, raised rates for a sixth time in three years and indicated another two increases are still expected this year.

docs.lead_paragraph: The Federal Reserve raised interest rates on Wednesday by a quarter of a percentage point and signaled that the central bank is on track to raise rates twice more in 2018.

headline.main: Fed Raises Interest Rates for Sixth Time Since Financial Crisis

docs.abstract: Mr. Kudlow, a CNBC commentator, is the leading candidate to head the National Economic Council.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Larry Kudlow, a CNBC television commentator who has informally advised President Trump on economic issues, is currently the top contender to head the National Economic Council, according to three people close to the president.

headline.main: Larry Kudlow Is the New Favorite to Replace Gary Cohn
headline.print_headline: Pundit Is Trump’s Pick  To Take Over Cohn’s Role As Top Economic Adviser

docs.abstract: A chaotic rollout of steel and aluminum tariffs, including a last-minute list of countries temporarily exempted from them, has left trade experts puzzled.
docs.snippet: A chaotic rollout of steel and aluminum tariffs, including a last-minute list of countries temporarily exempted from them, has left trade experts puzzled.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump’s flurry of trade moves this past week raised uncertainty and confusion among financial markets, trading partners, lawmakers and American industry, prompting many to ask what, exactly, his endgame might be.

headline.main: Trump’s Tariffs Keep Allies, Markets and Industry Guessing
headline.print_headline: Trump Tariffs Keep Allies And Industry Apprehensive

docs.abstract: The major credit card networks are ending a requirement that people sign for most card transactions — the latest blow to the signature.
docs.snippet: The major credit card networks are ending a requirement that people sign for most card transactions — the latest blow to the signature.
docs.lead_paragraph: For nearly a decade, Doug Taylor, a sales manager who travels often for work, has signed credit card receipts with a doodle of a dog wagging its tail.

headline.main: Credit Card Signatures Are About to Become Extinct in the U.S.
headline.print_headline: No More Hasty Scrawls: The End of Credit Card Signatures

docs.abstract: The Consumer Financial Protection Bureau might grant the banking industry’s wish to take offline a public database of complaints against the industry.
docs.snippet: The Consumer Financial Protection Bureau might grant the banking industry’s wish to take offline a public database of complaints against the industry.
docs.lead_paragraph: Financial companies have worked to diminish the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau’s powers since the day the agency was created. Now, they’re on the brink of having one of their top demands granted: an end to the regulator’s public database of complaints about their products and services.

headline.main: Consumer Bureau Looks to End Public View of Complaints Database
headline.print_headline: Watchdog Plans to End Public Access To Database
